{"type":"text","timestamp":1784313624420,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f7161375f0017SuIzhKKp5P3AV","messageID":"msg_f7160ead4001lkIQVoY4b2w5tf","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","type":"text","text":"I'm the `glm-max` lineage. Let me read Run 1's conclusions (to diverge from) and the prompt pack template.","time":{"start":1784313624415,"end":1784313624419}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784313624424,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_4e6bc826381e425aba03a9ef","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/run1-archive/research.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/run1-archive/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub defaultMode Policy\"\n3: description: \"Should a parent hub's routerPolicy.defaultMode point at a child mode or be null? Synthesis of 4 iterations (3 GPT-5.6-SOL + 1 Fable-5 diverse lens). Verdict: 1 keep (sk-prompt), 4 flip to null (cli-external, system-deep-loop, mcp-tooling, sk-design) — but the reframe matters: defaultMode is a defer-time suggestion + catch-all anchor, never an auto-route. Plus a simplified encoding rec and a live finding (sk-design still carries the over-emission bug).\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"default mode policy synthesis\"\n6:   - \"should hubs default to null verdict\"\n7:   - \"defaultMode defer-time suggestion\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"research\"\n10: ---\n11: \n12: # Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub `defaultMode` Policy\n13: \n14: **Method:** 4 iterations — 3 by GPT-5.6-SOL xhigh (semantics → decision rule + per-hub verdicts → encoding), 1 by Fable-5 as an adversarial diverse lens. (The runtime blocked SOL iters 4–5 on a workflow module-path bug; the 3 SOL iterations converged and the Fable lens independently verified them.)\n15: \n16: ---\n17: \n18: ## Bottom line\n19: \n20: The verdict survives adversarial review — **keep 1, flip 4** — but the *reason* changed, and that changes the fix.\n21: \n22: | Hub | Verdict | Confidence | Why |\n23: |---|---|---|---|\n24: | `sk-prompt` | **KEEP** | 0.85 | Its default is the catch-all scoring anchor and was deliberately re-affirmed this session with route-gold receipts. Not \"provisional\" — it's the one default with fresh evidence. |\n25: | `cli-external-orchestration` | **FLIP → null** | 0.80 | The correct suggestion is *runtime-dependent* (each executor refuses self-dispatch), so no static default can be right. Also neutralize its `defaultResource`. |\n26: | `system-deep-loop` | **FLIP → null** | 0.90 | Fully vestigial — prose already defers, no identity class, `defaultResource` is the neutral README. A zero-behavior-change truth reconciliation. |\n27: | `mcp-tooling` | **FLIP → null** | 0.85 | It's *already* the defer-with-suggestion pattern; the `defaultMode` field just misstates it. Keep the chrome-devtools hint via its existing fallback-only `defaultResource`. |\n28: | `sk-design` | **FLIP → null** | 0.75 | But null alone is insufficient — it also has `hub-identity` on all 6 modes (the over-emission bug), which must move to discovery-only classes. |\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## The reframe (the most important finding)\n33: \n34: `defaultMode` is **not an auto-route**. No hub in the fleet auto-executes a child on a zero-signal request — every one already *defers* (some with a suggested child). So \"keep vs flip\" was never a choice between auto-routing and deferring; nobody auto-routes.\n35: \n36: What a non-null `defaultMode` actually is, on a keyword-routed hub, is **two things**:\n37: 1. A **defer-time suggestion pointer** — \"if I have to ask, I'll lean toward this child.\"\n38: 2. A **catch-all scoring anchor** — the default mode is the one place the generic `hub-identity` vocabulary lives, so hub-generic words (like the bare word \"prompt\") score *one* mode instead of co-firing all of them. This is exactly the over-emission mechanism the whole fleet route-gold program fixed this session.\n39: \n40: Because of #2, on a well-built hub most \"generic\" requests never reach the zero-signal branch at all — they *score* the default. So the decision-theoretic \"expected loss of guessing vs deferring\" framing SOL built its rule on targets a branch that's rare by construction. The fleet's real, *measured* routing failure was on the scored path (six hubs blocked by over-emission), not the zero-signal branch.\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## Deterministic-benchmark fact (confirmed line-for-line)\n45: \n46: On a zero-signal request, a named-child default and `null` are **indistinguishable in the benchmark replay** — both produce `intents: []` and `workflowMode: null`; the *only* difference is a `defaultApplied` telemetry flag, and that flag means \"a default is *configured*,\" not \"the child was *selected*.\" So today's exact-set gold literally cannot tell a keep from a flip. (`router-replay.cjs:342-350`.)\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## The decision rule (refined)\n51: \n52: - **Default prior: defer-with-suggestion.** For a keyword-routed hub it strictly dominates both naked-defer (same safety, better UX) and auto-default (same UX hint, no mis-route) — no traffic corpus needed.\n53: - **Keep a non-null default only when it earns its keep** on *both* jobs: it's a safe lean for the plausible alternatives, AND it's serving as the catch-all anchor. sk-prompt passes both; the other four fail one or both.\n54: - SOL's formal expected-loss inequality is directionally right but *unfalsifiable in practice* (no zero-signal corpus exists) and unnecessary — the archetype rule below is the enforceable version.\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## Recommendations\n59: \n60: ### A. Router changes (per hub — each flip is a TWO-field decision, not one)\n61: 1. **sk-prompt** — keep as-is (it's the reference keyword-routed hub). Optionally close a minor unreachable pseudocode hole in its SKILL.md fallback branch.\n62: 2. **system-deep-loop** — flip `defaultMode: null`. Zero behavior change (metadata is dead). Safest flip.\n63: 3. **mcp-tooling** — flip `defaultMode: null`; keep the suggestion via its already-fallback-only `defaultResource`. Makes metadata match authored behavior.\n64: 4. **cli-external-orchestration** — flip `defaultMode: null` AND neutralize / mark fallback-only its `defaultResource` (else the cli-opencode bias survives in the resource channel).\n65: 5. **sk-design** — flip `defaultMode: null` **and** move `hub-identity` off all 6 modes to discovery-only classes. *Live finding:* sk-design currently carries the same over-emission bug fixed elsewhere this session; it escaped route-gold only because it has no routing-gold scenarios. This is the highest-value flip because it fixes a real latent defect.\n66: \n67: > **The fallback-resource rule — what `null` should point at.** When a hub can't pick a mode, the fallback must load the **routing helper**: the hub's `shared/references/smart_routing.md` (the intent→mode map) plus `mode-registry.json` (the mode menu). That points the request at *how to choose a mode* — never at a guessed child, never at neutral filler. The parent SKILL.md always stays in control (it *is* the router); the only real choice is which resource the fallback loads, and it should be the thing that helps route. So every flip is a two-field change: `defaultMode: null` **and** `defaultResource: [\"shared/references/smart_routing.md\", \"mode-registry.json\"]`.\n68: >\n69: > This corrects three current wrongs at once: the biased child pointers (sk-prompt, cli-external, mcp-tooling all load a *child* SKILL.md on fallback today), the vestigial filler (system-deep-loop → hub `README.md`, sk-design → four `shared/` vocab docs), and the two existing `null` hubs that also miss it (sk-doc → `quick_reference.md`, sk-code → `shared/README.md`). None of them load the mode-map, even though every hub ships one. Even `sk-prompt` (which keeps its default lean) should load the mode-map alongside it.\n70: \n71: ### B. Encoding — reject the heavy `zeroSignalPolicy` object; do the minimal delta instead\n72: Iteration 3 proposed a new `zeroSignalPolicy` object + a 9-field `expected_route` tuple. Fable showed ~70% already ships. The minimal, enforceable delta:\n73: 1. **Canonize a third archetype: \"defer-routed keyword hub\"** (`defaultMode: null`, `hub-identity` as discovery-only, and `defaultResource` pointing at the **routing helper** — `shared/references/smart_routing.md` + `mode-registry.json`, the mode-map — so the fallback helps pick the mode rather than suggesting a child). Today the canon blesses only *keyword-routed* (non-null default) and *detection-routed* (sk-code). The four flips create keyword hubs with null defaults, which the schema doesn't yet describe — without this third archetype the freshly hardened template will quietly pressure future authors back toward named defaults.\n74: 2. **Rename `defaultApplied` → `defaultConfigured`** (resolves the \"configured vs selected\" naming tension) and make it gold-assertable — the one new assertion that closes the keep-vs-null observability gap.\n75: 3. **Require `defaultResourceSemantics: \"fallback-only\"`** whenever `defaultMode` is non-null.\n76: 4. **One zero-signal route-gold fixture per hub**, whose gold matches its declared archetype. Fixtures are the evidence burden; prose `corpusRef`/`costModelRef` fields would go stale.\n77: 5. **Normalize the shipped defer-gold** `workflowMode` representation (currently `null` in one fixture, `[]` in another).\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## Where SOL and Fable agreed vs differed\n82: \n83: - **Agreed:** the replay semantics; the same five verdicts; that the named defaults were introduced by bulk scaffold/merge commits (the configuration is the hypothesis, not evidence); that mcp-tooling's metadata contradicts its behavior.\n84: - **Fable refined:** the reframe (defer-time suggestion + catch-all anchor, not auto-route); sk-prompt's keep is *under-claimed* not provisional (it has same-day receipts); the vestigial-vs-backed `defaultResource` split (SOL never checked `defaultResource`); cli's static-default is *unrepresentable* (runtime-dependent); sk-design needs the hub-identity move; the encoding is over-engineered.\n85: \n86: ---\n87: \n88: ## Honest scope\n89: \n90: - 3 SOL iterations (converged) + 1 Fable diverse lens = 4 of the requested 5; the runtime blocked SOL iters 4–5 (environmental workflow bug on resume, not a research gap).\n91: - All verdicts are **proposals** — changing a shipped `defaultMode` is a live-routing behavior change. sk-design's hub-identity fix is the one with a confirmed defect behind it; the other flips are truth-reconciliation (metadata matching already-authored defer behavior).\n92: - No corpus of real zero-signal traffic exists; the recommendation deliberately routes around needing one (archetype + fixtures, not statistics).\n\n(End of file - total 92 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub defaultMode Policy\"\ndescription: \"Should a parent hub's routerPolicy.defaultMode point at a child mode or be null? Synthesis of 4 iterations (3 GPT-5.6-SOL + 1 Fable-5 diverse lens). Verdict: 1 keep (sk-prompt), 4 flip to null (cli-external, system-deep-loop, mcp-tooling, sk-design) — but the reframe matters: defaultMode is a defer-time suggestion + catch-all anchor, never an auto-route. Plus a simplified encoding rec and a live finding (sk-design still carries the over-emission bug).\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"default mode policy synthesis\"\n  - \"should hubs default to null verdict\"\n  - \"defaultMode defer-time suggestion\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"research\"\n---\n\n# Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub `defaultMode` Policy\n\n**Method:** 4 iterations — 3 by GPT-5.6-SOL xhigh (semantics → decision rule + per-hub verdicts → encoding), 1 by Fable-5 as an adversarial diverse lens. (The runtime blocked SOL iters 4–5 on a workflow module-path bug; the 3 SOL iterations converged and the Fable lens independently verified them.)\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nThe verdict survives adversarial review — **keep 1, flip 4** — but the *reason* changed, and that changes the fix.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/run1-archive/research.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub defaultMode Policy\"\ndescription: \"Should a parent hub's routerPolicy.defaultMode point at a child mode or be null? Synthesis of 4 iterations (3 GPT-5.6-SOL + 1 Fable-5 diverse lens). Verdict: 1 keep (sk-prompt), 4 flip to null (cli-external, system-deep-loop, mcp-tooling, sk-design) — but the reframe matters: defaultMode is a defer-time suggestion + catch-all anchor, never an auto-route. Plus a simplified encoding rec and a live finding (sk-design still carries the over-emission bug).\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"default mode policy synthesis\"\n  - \"should hubs default to null verdict\"\n  - \"defaultMode defer-time suggestion\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"research\"\n---\n\n# Research Synthesis: Parent-Hub `defaultMode` Policy\n\n**Method:** 4 iterations — 3 by GPT-5.6-SOL xhigh (semantics → decision rule + per-hub verdicts → encoding), 1 by Fable-5 as an adversarial diverse lens. (The runtime blocked SOL iters 4–5 on a workflow module-path bug; the 3 SOL iterations converged and the Fable lens independently verified them.)\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nThe verdict survives adversarial review — **keep 1, flip 4** — but the *reason* changed, and that changes the fix.\n\n| Hub | Verdict | Confidence | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `sk-prompt` | **KEEP** | 0.85 | Its default is the catch-all scoring anchor and was deliberately re-affirmed this session with route-gold receipts. Not \"provisional\" — it's the one default with fresh evidence. |\n| `cli-external-orchestration` | **FLIP → null** | 0.80 | The correct suggestion is *runtime-dependent* (each executor refuses self-dispatch), so no static default can be right. Also neutralize its `defaultResource`. |\n| `system-deep-loop` | **FLIP → null** | 0.90 | Fully vestigial — prose already defers, no identity class, `defaultResource` is the neutral README. A zero-behavior-change truth reconciliation. |\n| `mcp-tooling` | **FLIP → null** | 0.85 | It's *already* the defer-with-suggestion pattern; the `defaultMode` field just misstates it. Keep the chrome-devtools hint via its existing fallback-only `defaultResource`. |\n| `sk-design` | **FLIP → null** | 0.75 | But null alone is insufficient — it also has `hub-identity` on all 6 modes (the over-emission bug), which must move to discovery-only classes. |\n\n---\n\n## The reframe (the most important finding)\n\n`defaultMode` is **not an auto-route**. No hub in the fleet auto-executes a child on a zero-signal request — every one already *defers* (some with a suggested child). So \"keep vs flip\" was never a choice between auto-routing and deferring; nobody auto-routes.\n\nWhat a non-null `defaultMode` actually is, on a keyword-routed hub, is **two things**:\n1. A **defer-time suggestion pointer** — \"if I have to ask, I'll lean toward this child.\"\n2. A **catch-all scoring anchor** — the default mode is the one place the generic `hub-identity` vocabulary lives, so hub-generic words (like the bare word \"prompt\") score *one* mode instead of co-firing all of them. This is exactly the over-emission mechanism the whole fleet route-gold program fixed this session.\n\nBecause of #2, on a well-built hub most \"generic\" requests never reach the zero-signal branch at all — they *score* the default. So the decision-theoretic \"expected loss of guessing vs deferring\" framing SOL built its rule on targets a branch that's rare by construction. The fleet's real, *measured* routing failure was on the scored path (six hubs blocked by over-emission), not the zero-signal branch.\n\n---\n\n## Deterministic-benchmark fact (confirmed line-for-line)\n\nOn a zero-signal request, a named-child default and `null` are **indistinguishable in the benchmark replay** — both produce `intents: []` and `workflowMode: null`; the *only* difference is a `defaultApplied` telemetry flag, and that flag means \"a default is *configured*,\" not \"the child was *selected*.\" So today's exact-set gold literally cannot tell a keep from a flip. (`router-replay.cjs:342-350`.)\n\n---\n\n## The decision rule (refined)\n\n- **Default prior: defer-with-suggestion.** For a keyword-routed hub it strictly dominates both naked-defer (same safety, better UX) and auto-default (same UX hint, no mis-route) — no traffic corpus needed.\n- **Keep a non-null default only when it earns its keep** on *both* jobs: it's a safe lean for the plausible alternatives, AND it's serving as the catch-all anchor. sk-prompt passes both; the other four fail one or both.\n- SOL's formal expected-loss inequality is directionally right but *unfalsifiable in practice* (no zero-signal corpus exists) and unnecessary — the archetype rule below is the enforceable version.\n\n---\n\n## Recommendations\n\n### A. Router changes (per hub — each flip is a TWO-field decision, not one)\n1. **sk-prompt** — keep as-is (it's the reference keyword-routed hub). Optionally close a minor unreachable pseudocode hole in its SKILL.md fallback branch.\n2. **system-deep-loop** — flip `defaultMode: null`. Zero behavior change (metadata is dead). Safest flip.\n3. **mcp-tooling** — flip `defaultMode: null`; keep the suggestion via its already-fallback-only `defaultResource`. Makes metadata match authored behavior.\n4. **cli-external-orchestration** — flip `defaultMode: null` AND neutralize / mark fallback-only its `defaultResource` (else the cli-opencode bias survives in the resource channel).\n5. **sk-design** — flip `defaultMode: null` **and** move `hub-identity` off all 6 modes to discovery-only classes. *Live finding:* sk-design currently carries the same over-emission bug fixed elsewhere this session; it escaped route-gold only because it has no routing-gold scenarios. This is the highest-value flip because it fixes a real latent defect.\n\n> **The fallback-resource rule — what `null` should point at.** When a hub can't pick a mode, the fallback must load the **routing helper**: the hub's `shared/references/smart_routing.md` (the intent→mode map) plus `mode-registry.json` (the mode menu). That points the request at *how to choose a mode* — never at a guessed child, never at neutral filler. The parent SKILL.md always stays in control (it *is* the router); the only real choice is which resource the fallback loads, and it should be the thing that helps route. So every flip is a two-field change: `defaultMode: null` **and** `defaultResource: [\"shared/references/smart_routing.md\", \"mode-registry.json\"]`.\n>\n> This corrects three current wrongs at once: the biased child pointers (sk-prompt, cli-external, mcp-tooling all load a *child* SKILL.md on fallback today), the vestigial filler (system-deep-loop → hub `README.md`, sk-design → four `shared/` vocab docs), and the two existing `null` hubs that also miss it (sk-doc → `quick_reference.md`, sk-code → `shared/README.md`). None of them load the mode-map, even though every hub ships one. Even `sk-prompt` (which keeps its default lean) should load the mode-map alongside it.\n\n### B. Encoding — reject the heavy `zeroSignalPolicy` object; do the minimal delta instead\nIteration 3 proposed a new `zeroSignalPolicy` object + a 9-field `expected_route` tuple. Fable showed ~70% already ships. The minimal, enforceable delta:\n1. **Canonize a third archetype: \"defer-routed keyword hub\"** (`defaultMode: null`, `hub-identity` as discovery-only, and `defaultResource` pointing at the **routing helper** — `shared/references/smart_routing.md` + `mode-registry.json`, the mode-map — so the fallback helps pick the mode rather than suggesting a child). Today the canon blesses only *keyword-routed* (non-null default) and *detection-routed* (sk-code). The four flips create keyword hubs with null defaults, which the schema doesn't yet describe — without this third archetype the freshly hardened template will quietly pressure future authors back toward named defaults.\n2. **Rename `defaultApplied` → `defaultConfigured`** (resolves the \"configured vs selected\" naming tension) and make it gold-assertable — the one new assertion that closes the keep-vs-null observability gap.\n3. **Require `defaultResourceSemantics: \"fallback-only\"`** whenever `defaultMode` is non-null.\n4. **One zero-signal route-gold fixture per hub**, whose gold matches its declared archetype. Fixtures are the evidence burden; prose `corpusRef`/`costModelRef` fields would go stale.\n5. **Normalize the shipped defer-gold** `workflowMode` representation (currently `null` in one fixture, `[]` in another).\n\n---\n\n## Where SOL and Fable agreed vs differed\n\n- **Agreed:** the replay semantics; the same five verdicts; that the named defaults were introduced by bulk scaffold/merge commits (the configuration is the hypothesis, not evidence); that mcp-tooling's metadata contradicts its behavior.\n- **Fable refined:** the reframe (defer-time suggestion + catch-all anchor, not auto-route); sk-prompt's keep is *under-claimed* not provisional (it has same-day receipts); the vestigial-vs-backed `defaultResource` split (SOL never checked `defaultResource`); cli's static-default is *unrepresentable* (runtime-dependent); sk-design needs the hub-identity move; the encoding is over-engineered.\n\n---\n\n## Honest scope\n\n- 3 SOL iterations (converged) + 1 Fable diverse lens = 4 of the requested 5; the runtime blocked SOL iters 4–5 (environmental workflow bug on resume, not a research gap).\n- All verdicts are **proposals** — changing a shipped `defaultMode` is a live-routing behavior change. sk-design's hub-identity fix is the one with a confirmed defect behind it; the other flips are truth-reconciliation (metadata matching already-authored defer behavior).\n- No corpus of real zero-signal traffic exists; the recommendation deliberately routes around needing one (archetype + fixtures, not statistics).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":92,"totalLines":92,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/run1-archive/research.md","time":{"start":1784313624418,"end":1784313624423}},"id":"prt_f716137610010Rdlnw8CXMqMTT","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","messageID":"msg_f7160ead4001lkIQVoY4b2w5tf"}}
