{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784314317840,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f716bcc0c001YkkGSFYKBZ1PF8","messageID":"msg_f716baa0100148HqbNYEJHiPKr","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","snapshot":"06ab70fdf2456a839c5f270652a3d8322362640a","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1784314328733,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f716bf4a4001upQHiP5qgkqSlL","messageID":"msg_f716baa0100148HqbNYEJHiPKr","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","type":"text","text":"Smoking gun found. `smart_routing.md` has `DEFAULT_RESOURCE = []` (emits only on positive score), but `hub-router.json` shows every mode carries a `\"hub-identity\"` class — the over-emission disease Run 1 flagged. Let me confirm the canon template's `defaultResource` semantics.","time":{"start":1784314328228,"end":1784314328732}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784314328739,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8f64031bf00c4bfd8ff3b30a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"_template\": \"Parent-skill hub-router.json scaffold. Replace every [bracketed] placeholder. Keep routerSignals keys bidirectionally aligned with mode-registry.json modes[].workflowMode. The canonical live example is sk-code/hub-router.json.\",\n3:   \"_surfaceBundleNote\": \"The surfaceBundle outcome and its bundleRule are surface-axis only; a pure workflow hub keeps only single, orderedBundle, and defer (checker 5f/5g).\",\n4:   \"_pathContract\": \"Two path kinds live in a hub and must never be conflated. A hubLoadAddress is what routerSignals[].resources hold: a packet entrypoint the hub loads (e.g. [workflow-packet-a]/SKILL.md). A leafResourceId is the canonical packet-root-relative resource id (references/... or assets/...) that the second-layer surface router (shared/references/smart_routing.md, scaffolded from parent_skill_smart_routing_template.md) maps each intent to. A raw path is converted to the canonical (workflowMode, leafResourceId) pair at exactly one boundary — the leaf-resource contract library — via a packet-qualified prefix ([packet]/references|assets/...) or an authored shared alias (leaf-aliases.json). Never strip a prefix generically and never infer a shared-tier file into a mode.\",\n5:   \"_routingPrecisionNote\": \"Catch-all vocabulary classes (hub-identity here) belong on the DEFAULT mode only — never on specialized modes. Intent scoring is binary (a mode gets its full weight if ANY of its classes matches, else 0) and selection keeps every intent within routerPolicy.ambiguityDelta of the top score, so a class shared across modes makes them all co-fire on hub-generic words: over-emission that fails the route-gold gate. Each specialized mode must fire only on its own vocabulary; hub-generic words then route to the default (or defer). To make one specific signal win alone over the default, give it a weight gap wider than the ambiguity delta rather than a shared class.\",\n6:   \"skill\": \"[parent-skill-name]\",\n7:   \"version\": \"1.0.0.0\",\n8:   \"routerPolicy\": {\n9:     \"defaultMode\": \"[workflow-mode-a]\",\n10:     \"ambiguityDelta\": 1,\n11:     \"tieBreak\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow-mode-b]\", \"[workflow-mode-c]\", \"[surface-name]\"],\n12:     \"outcomes\": {\n13:       \"single\": \"one dominant workflow intent routes to one workflow mode\",\n14:       \"orderedBundle\": \"clearly separate workflow intents route to an ordered workflow mode list\",\n15:       \"surfaceBundle\": \"CONDITIONAL (declare only if this hub has packetKind:surface packets; delete for a pure workflow hub) — one workflow mode primary plus zero-or-more read-only surface packets as evidence, workflow ordered first\",\n16:       \"defer\": \"unclear or contradictory intent asks for disambiguation\"\n17:     },\n18:     \"defaultResource\": [\"[shared-or-workflow-resource].md\"],\n19:     \"bundleRules\": [\n20:       {\n21:         \"_example\": \"Optional surfaceBundle rule: DELETE for a pure workflow hub because includeSurfaces names a surface mode that a workflow-only hub lacks (checker 5f). When whenPrimary routes, attach includeSurfaces as read-only evidence. Every named mode must be a real mode-registry.json entry.\",\n22:         \"name\": \"[workflow-mode-a]-with-surface-evidence\",\n23:         \"whenPrimary\": \"[workflow-mode-a]\",\n24:         \"includeSurfaces\": [\"[surface-name]\"],\n25:         \"outcome\": \"surfaceBundle\"\n26:       },\n27:       {\n28:         \"_example\": \"Optional orderedBundle rule: when whenAll workflow modes co-occur, emit them as one ordered bundle.\",\n29:         \"name\": \"[workflow-mode-a]-then-[workflow-mode-b]\",\n30:         \"whenAll\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow-mode-b]\"],\n31:         \"outcome\": \"orderedBundle\"\n32:       }\n33:     ]\n34:   },\n35:   \"routerSignals\": {\n36:     \"[workflow-mode-a]\": {\n37:       \"_note\": \"This is defaultMode; it alone carries hub-identity so hub-generic words route here. Do NOT add hub-identity to the specialized modes below (see _routingPrecisionNote).\",\n38:       \"weight\": 4,\n39:       \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]-aliases\", \"[workflow-mode-a]-actions\", \"hub-identity\"],\n40:       \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-a]/SKILL.md\"]\n41:     },\n42:     \"[workflow-mode-b]\": {\n43:       \"weight\": 4,\n44:       \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-b]-aliases\", \"[workflow-mode-b]-evidence\"],\n45:       \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-b]/SKILL.md\"]\n46:     },\n47:     \"[workflow-mode-c]\": {\n48:       \"weight\": 3,\n49:       \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-c]-aliases\"],\n50:       \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-c]/SKILL.md\"]\n51:     },\n52:     \"[surface-name]\": {\n53:       \"_example\": \"Surface packet signal: normal router entry, read-only resources, metadata route in mode-registry.json.\",\n54:       \"weight\": 2,\n55:       \"classes\": [\"[surface-name]-aliases\", \"[surface-name]-runtime\"],\n56:       \"resources\": [\"[surface-name]/SKILL.md\", \"[surface-name]/references/[reference].md\"]\n57:     }\n58:   },\n59:   \"vocabularyClasses\": {\n60:     \"hub-identity\": {\n61:       \"keywords\": [\"[parent-skill-name]\", \"mode-registry\", \"hub-router\", \"workflowmode\", \"packetkind\", \"[domain keyword]\"]\n62:     },\n63:     \"[workflow-mode-a]-aliases\": {\n64:       \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n65:     },\n66:     \"[workflow-mode-a]-actions\": {\n67:       \"keywords\": [\"[action verb]\", \"[workflow action phrase]\"]\n68:     },\n69:     \"[workflow-mode-b]-aliases\": {\n70:       \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-b]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n71:     },\n72:     \"[workflow-mode-b]-evidence\": {\n73:       \"keywords\": [\"[evidence phrase]\", \"[verification phrase]\"]\n74:     },\n75:     \"[workflow-mode-c]-aliases\": {\n76:       \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-c]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n77:     },\n78:     \"[surface-name]-aliases\": {\n79:       \"keywords\": [\"[surface-name]\", \"[surface phrase]\", \"[surface natural-language alias]\"]\n80:     },\n81:     \"[surface-name]-runtime\": {\n82:       \"keywords\": [\"[surface runtime keyword]\", \"[surface framework keyword]\", \"[surface evidence keyword]\"]\n83:     }\n84:   }\n85: }\n\n(End of file - total 85 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"_template\": \"Parent-skill hub-router.json scaffold. Replace every [bracketed] placeholder. Keep routerSignals keys bidirectionally aligned with mode-registry.json modes[].workflowMode. The canonical live example is sk-code/hub-router.json.\",\n  \"_surfaceBundleNote\": \"The surfaceBundle outcome and its bundleRule are surface-axis only; a pure workflow hub keeps only single, orderedBundle, and defer (checker 5f/5g).\",\n  \"_pathContract\": \"Two path kinds live in a hub and must never be conflated. A hubLoadAddress is what routerSignals[].resources hold: a packet entrypoint the hub loads (e.g. [workflow-packet-a]/SKILL.md). A leafResourceId is the canonical packet-root-relative resource id (references/... or assets/...) that the second-layer surface router (shared/references/smart_routing.md, scaffolded from parent_skill_smart_routing_template.md) maps each intent to. A raw path is converted to the canonical (workflowMode, leafResourceId) pair at exactly one boundary — the leaf-resource contract library — via a packet-qualified prefix ([packet]/references|assets/...) or an authored shared alias (leaf-aliases.json). Never strip a prefix generically and never infer a shared-tier file into a mode.\",\n  \"_routingPrecisionNote\": \"Catch-all vocabulary classes (hub-identity here) belong on the DEFAULT mode only — never on specialized modes. Intent scoring is binary (a mode gets its full weight if ANY of its classes matches, else 0) and selection keeps every intent within routerPolicy.ambiguityDelta of the top score, so a class shared across modes makes them all co-fire on hub-generic words: over-emission that fails the route-gold gate. Each specialized mode must fire only on its own vocabulary; hub-generic words then route to the default (or defer). To make one specific signal win alone over the default, give it a weight gap wider than the ambiguity delta rather than a shared class.\",\n  \"skill\": \"[parent-skill-name]\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0.0\",\n  \"routerPolicy\": {\n    \"defaultMode\": \"[workflow-mode-a]\",\n    \"ambiguityDelta\": 1,\n    \"tieBreak\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow-mode-b]\", \"[workflow-mode-c]\", \"[surface-name]\"],\n    \"outcomes\": {\n      \"single\": \"one dominant workflow intent routes to one workflow mode\",\n      \"orderedBundle\": \"clearly separate workflow intents route to an ordered workflow mode list\",\n      \"surfaceBundle\": \"CONDITIONAL (declare only if this hub has packetKind:surface packets; delete for a pure workflow hub) — one workflow mode primary plus zero-or-more read-only surface packets as evidence, workflow ordered first\",\n      \"defer\": \"unclear or contradictory intent asks for disambiguation\"\n    },\n    \"defaultResource\": [\"[shared-or-workflow-resource].md\"],\n    \"bundleRules\": [\n      {","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json","text":"{\n  \"_template\": \"Parent-skill hub-router.json scaffold. Replace every [bracketed] placeholder. Keep routerSignals keys bidirectionally aligned with mode-registry.json modes[].workflowMode. The canonical live example is sk-code/hub-router.json.\",\n  \"_surfaceBundleNote\": \"The surfaceBundle outcome and its bundleRule are surface-axis only; a pure workflow hub keeps only single, orderedBundle, and defer (checker 5f/5g).\",\n  \"_pathContract\": \"Two path kinds live in a hub and must never be conflated. A hubLoadAddress is what routerSignals[].resources hold: a packet entrypoint the hub loads (e.g. [workflow-packet-a]/SKILL.md). A leafResourceId is the canonical packet-root-relative resource id (references/... or assets/...) that the second-layer surface router (shared/references/smart_routing.md, scaffolded from parent_skill_smart_routing_template.md) maps each intent to. A raw path is converted to the canonical (workflowMode, leafResourceId) pair at exactly one boundary — the leaf-resource contract library — via a packet-qualified prefix ([packet]/references|assets/...) or an authored shared alias (leaf-aliases.json). Never strip a prefix generically and never infer a shared-tier file into a mode.\",\n  \"_routingPrecisionNote\": \"Catch-all vocabulary classes (hub-identity here) belong on the DEFAULT mode only — never on specialized modes. Intent scoring is binary (a mode gets its full weight if ANY of its classes matches, else 0) and selection keeps every intent within routerPolicy.ambiguityDelta of the top score, so a class shared across modes makes them all co-fire on hub-generic words: over-emission that fails the route-gold gate. Each specialized mode must fire only on its own vocabulary; hub-generic words then route to the default (or defer). To make one specific signal win alone over the default, give it a weight gap wider than the ambiguity delta rather than a shared class.\",\n  \"skill\": \"[parent-skill-name]\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0.0\",\n  \"routerPolicy\": {\n    \"defaultMode\": \"[workflow-mode-a]\",\n    \"ambiguityDelta\": 1,\n    \"tieBreak\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow-mode-b]\", \"[workflow-mode-c]\", \"[surface-name]\"],\n    \"outcomes\": {\n      \"single\": \"one dominant workflow intent routes to one workflow mode\",\n      \"orderedBundle\": \"clearly separate workflow intents route to an ordered workflow mode list\",\n      \"surfaceBundle\": \"CONDITIONAL (declare only if this hub has packetKind:surface packets; delete for a pure workflow hub) — one workflow mode primary plus zero-or-more read-only surface packets as evidence, workflow ordered first\",\n      \"defer\": \"unclear or contradictory intent asks for disambiguation\"\n    },\n    \"defaultResource\": [\"[shared-or-workflow-resource].md\"],\n    \"bundleRules\": [\n      {\n        \"_example\": \"Optional surfaceBundle rule: DELETE for a pure workflow hub because includeSurfaces names a surface mode that a workflow-only hub lacks (checker 5f). When whenPrimary routes, attach includeSurfaces as read-only evidence. Every named mode must be a real mode-registry.json entry.\",\n        \"name\": \"[workflow-mode-a]-with-surface-evidence\",\n        \"whenPrimary\": \"[workflow-mode-a]\",\n        \"includeSurfaces\": [\"[surface-name]\"],\n        \"outcome\": \"surfaceBundle\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"_example\": \"Optional orderedBundle rule: when whenAll workflow modes co-occur, emit them as one ordered bundle.\",\n        \"name\": \"[workflow-mode-a]-then-[workflow-mode-b]\",\n        \"whenAll\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow-mode-b]\"],\n        \"outcome\": \"orderedBundle\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"routerSignals\": {\n    \"[workflow-mode-a]\": {\n      \"_note\": \"This is defaultMode; it alone carries hub-identity so hub-generic words route here. Do NOT add hub-identity to the specialized modes below (see _routingPrecisionNote).\",\n      \"weight\": 4,\n      \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]-aliases\", \"[workflow-mode-a]-actions\", \"hub-identity\"],\n      \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-a]/SKILL.md\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-b]\": {\n      \"weight\": 4,\n      \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-b]-aliases\", \"[workflow-mode-b]-evidence\"],\n      \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-b]/SKILL.md\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-c]\": {\n      \"weight\": 3,\n      \"classes\": [\"[workflow-mode-c]-aliases\"],\n      \"resources\": [\"[workflow-packet-c]/SKILL.md\"]\n    },\n    \"[surface-name]\": {\n      \"_example\": \"Surface packet signal: normal router entry, read-only resources, metadata route in mode-registry.json.\",\n      \"weight\": 2,\n      \"classes\": [\"[surface-name]-aliases\", \"[surface-name]-runtime\"],\n      \"resources\": [\"[surface-name]/SKILL.md\", \"[surface-name]/references/[reference].md\"]\n    }\n  },\n  \"vocabularyClasses\": {\n    \"hub-identity\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[parent-skill-name]\", \"mode-registry\", \"hub-router\", \"workflowmode\", \"packetkind\", \"[domain keyword]\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-a]-aliases\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-a]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-a]-actions\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[action verb]\", \"[workflow action phrase]\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-b]-aliases\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-b]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-b]-evidence\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[evidence phrase]\", \"[verification phrase]\"]\n    },\n    \"[workflow-mode-c]-aliases\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[workflow-mode-c]\", \"[workflow phrase]\", \"[natural-language alias]\"]\n    },\n    \"[surface-name]-aliases\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[surface-name]\", \"[surface phrase]\", \"[surface natural-language alias]\"]\n    },\n    \"[surface-name]-runtime\": {\n      \"keywords\": [\"[surface runtime keyword]\", \"[surface framework keyword]\", \"[surface evidence keyword]\"]\n    }\n  }\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":85,"totalLines":85,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json","time":{"start":1784314328731,"end":1784314328738}},"id":"prt_f716bf69a001I0xpOij32QLlmA","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","messageID":"msg_f716baa0100148HqbNYEJHiPKr"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784314329103,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f716bf80d001wEbD8G5T8YKdY5","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"06ab70fdf2456a839c5f270652a3d8322362640a","messageID":"msg_f716baa0100148HqbNYEJHiPKr","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":126842,"input":3320,"output":126,"reasoning":772,"cache":{"write":0,"read":122624}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784314337638,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f716c1961001E8HM4xXBRJLs7N","messageID":"msg_f716bf9500018pbD4Pohv7CsVy","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","snapshot":"06ab70fdf2456a839c5f270652a3d8322362640a","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1784314380051,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"id":"prt_f716c4ab5001makw99uiim69D6","messageID":"msg_f716bf9500018pbD4Pohv7CsVy","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","type":"text","text":"Decisive. The canon template (line 5, 37, 60) explicitly encodes \"hub-identity belongs on the DEFAULT mode only\" — the exact mechanism behind the catch-all-anchor. This yields a sharp second-order finding: nulling the default removes hub-identity's home, creating new failure modes. Writing iteration 3.","time":{"start":1784314350261,"end":1784314380050}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784314380053,"sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_4d48841dc25d407e8c144130","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Iteration 3: Second-Order Anti-Patterns of `null + mode-map` (Does the Fix Recreate the Disease?)\n\n**Thread:** 7 (second-order effects) | **Lineage:** glm-max | **Focus:** Q3\n**Run:** 3 of 5 | **Status:** complete | **Timestamp:** 2026-07-17T18:55:00Z\n\n## Focus\n\nRun 1 prescribed null's fallback should load the routing helper (`smart_routing.md` + `mode-registry.json`). This iteration inverts the recommendation and asks: what NEW failure modes does that introduce? Specifically — does loading the full mode-map on a zero-signal request recreate the **catch-all-bias over-emission disease** that Run 1 spent the session curing? And what second-order costs (over-deferring, stale registries, menu-vs-scorer conflation) come bundled with null+mode-map?\n\n## Findings\n\n### F3.1 — The canon ALREADY encodes the rule that ties the over-emission disease to the default — confirmed line-for-line.\n\nThe create-skill canon's `parent_skill_hub_router_template.json` is explicit and repeated:\n\n- `_routingPrecisionNote`: \"Catch-all vocabulary classes (hub-identity here) belong on the DEFAULT mode only — never on specialized modes... a class shared across modes makes them all co-fire on hub-generic words: over-emission that fails the route-gold gate.\" [SOURCE: file:.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json:5]\n- The default mode's signal note: \"This is defaultMode; it alone carries hub-identity so hub-generic words route here. Do NOT add hub-identity to the specialized modes below.\" [SOURCE: file:.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json:37]\n- The `hub-identity` vocabulary class is the skill's own name + meta-terms (`mode-registry`, `hub-router`, `workflowmode`). [SOURCE: file:.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json:60-62]\n\n**Why this matters for the flips:** Run 1's reframe (\"defaultMode is a catch-all scoring anchor\") is not opinion — it is the canon's *named mechanism*. The default mode is the ONLY legal home for hub-generic vocabulary. So \"flip to null\" is not just removing a fallback pointer; it is **evicting hub-identity's only scoring home.** That eviction is the entire point (it stops the bias) but it is also the seed of every second-order cost below.\n\n### F3.2 — Anti-pattern A1: \"the skill's own name becomes unrouteable\" (over-deferring friction).\n\nWith `defaultMode: null` and hub-identity correctly removed from all modes, the skill's own name (`design`, `sk-design`, `prompt`) scores **no mode**. A request that is just the skill name with no specific axis — \"help me with design\", \"use sk-design\" — falls to the zero-signal defer branch every time. This is maximally *safe* (no mis-route) but can be maximally *annoying* if name-only requests are common. The cost is real but bounded: the advisor selects the skill on the name, and the hub's defer surfaces a disambiguation card, so the user gets a *menu* (not a dead end). The friction is one extra turn, not a failure. **Verdict: acceptable, but the canon should name it as the expected cost of null so authors don't re-add a default to suppress it.**\n\n### F3.3 — Anti-pattern A2: \"mode-map-as-new-catch-all-bias\" — the fix recreating the disease, but ONLY if the menu is scored, not presented.\n\nThis is the central second-order risk. Run 1 said load `smart_routing.md` + `mode-registry.json` on the null fallback. The two resources behave differently:\n\n- **`smart_routing.md` is SAFE as a fallback resource.** Its `DEFAULT_RESOURCE = []` — \"No always-loaded preamble on the positive leaf axis... Leaf routing loads only the selected mode's set.\" [SOURCE: file:.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/references/smart_routing.md:72-75] It emits typed leaves ONLY on a positive intent score; on zero-signal it loads nothing. Loading it as a fallback resource does NOT recreate bias.\n- **`mode-registry.json` is a MENU, not a scorer.** It lists modes with their `aliases` (color, motion, audit — mode-specific vocabulary, NOT hub-generic). [SOURCE: file:.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json:55-118] Loading it is safe ONLY IF the agent treats it as a **disambiguation card to present** (\"here are the 6 modes; which axis?\"), NOT as a routing resource to score against.\n\n**The latent disease:** if a future author, trying to make the menu \"smarter,\" adds hub-identity vocabulary to `mode-registry.json` (e.g. tagging every mode with the skill name so the menu \"feels complete\"), loading it on fallback would re-introduce exactly the co-fire over-emission the canon forbids. **Verdict: Run 1's \"load both\" is correct ONLY with an explicit semantics split — `defaultResourceSemantics: \"disambiguation-card\"` for the menu, distinct from a scored routing resource. The canon must forbid hub-identity vocabulary in any resource loaded as a fallback scorer.**\n\n### F3.4 — Anti-pattern A3: stale-registry drift becomes USER-VISIBLE (a new maintenance coupling).\n\nToday `mode-registry.json` is an internal routing artifact. Under null+mode-map, it becomes a **user-facing** artifact — it is the menu shown on defer. If `mode-registry.json` drifts from `hub-router.json` signals (a mode added to one but not the other), the agent asks the user to pick from a menu that does not match what actually scores. Pre-null, a stale registry was an internal routing bug; post-null, it is a user-facing lie. **Verdict: null+mode-map elevates `mode-registry.json` freshness from internal to user-visible — it needs the same drift-validation the canon applies to `hub-router.json`, or a single-source rule that the menu is derived from the router (not independently authored).**\n\n### F3.5 — Anti-pattern A4: \"the compressed card vs full registry\" shape question (spec thread 1).\n\nThe mode-menu for disambiguation does not need to be the full machine-readable `mode-registry.json` (which is large and includes `toolSurface`, `backendKind`, etc. irrelevant to a user choice). A **compressed disambiguation card** — one line per mode: `mode — one-sentence purpose — 2-3 example triggers` — serves the defer branch better: small token cost, unambiguous, human-readable. The full registry stays the machine source-of-truth; the card is the presentation layer. **Verdict: the canon should specify the fallback loads a *compressed card* derived from the registry, not the raw registry — this bounds token cost and removes the temptation to score the menu.**\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- `file:.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/parent_skill/parent_skill_hub_router_template.json:5,37,60` (hub-identity-on-default-only canon rule)\n- `file:.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/references/smart_routing.md:72-75,146` (DEFAULT_RESOURCE=[]; zero-signal → default or disambiguate)\n- `file:.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json:55-118` (aliases are mode-specific, not hub-generic)\n- `file:.opencode/skills/sk-design/hub-router.json` (routerSignals; hub-identity class on modes — the live sk-design over-emission bug)\n- `file:.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/run1-archive/research.md` (Run 1 \"load both\" recommendation)\n\n## Assessment\n\n- **newInfoRatio: 0.70** — Genuine second-order stress test. Discovers the canon already names the disease mechanism (hub-identity-on-default), and that Run 1's \"load both\" prescription is correct ONLY with an explicit menu-vs-scorer semantics split and a compressed-card presentation layer. Net-new: A1 (name-unrouteable), A3 (registry drift becomes user-visible), A4 (compressed card shape).\n- **Novelty justification:** Run 1 asserted the fallback rule without stress-testing it. This iteration derives four concrete anti-patterns from the canon's own hub-identity rule and proposes a semantics split (`disambiguation-card` vs scored resource) Run 1 did not reach.\n- **Confidence:** 0.85 (canon rule is line-cited; the anti-patterns are mechanical consequences, not speculation. A1's \"how common are name-only requests\" is the one empirical unknown, deliberately routed around per Run 1's no-corpus stance).\n\n## Reflection\n\n- **What worked:** Reading the canon *template* (not just live hubs) surfaced the hub-identity-on-default rule as an explicit, named invariant — which is the load-bearing fact for the whole second-order analysis. The template's `_routingPrecisionNote` is the Rosetta stone.\n- **What failed / ruled out:** Ruled out: \"loading smart_routing.md recreates the bias\" (false — its DEFAULT_RESOURCE=[]). Confirmed-and-refined: \"loading mode-registry.json is safe\" — safe ONLY as a presented menu, NOT as a scored resource.\n- **Carried-forward:** The semantics split (`defaultResourceSemantics: \"disambiguation-card\"` vs `\"fallback-only\"` vs scored) is an encoding delta. It connects to Q4 (single-mode hubs make the menu trivial → no card needed) and Q5 (contrarian: a named default sidesteps ALL of A1–A4 at the cost of one mis-route — is that the better tradeoff?).\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\n**Iteration 4 → Q4 (thread 9):** Edge cases that break the archetype rule. Single-mode hubs (no menu to disambiguate — does null degenerate to \"load the only mode\"?), empty mode-map, registry drift mechanics, and generalizing cli's *contextual* (runtime-dependent) default into a typed concept. Which edge cases expose a flaw in the per-axis archetype taxonomy from iter 2?\n","filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-003.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0063-skilled-router-collapse/.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-003.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/021-default-mode-policy-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-003.md","time":{"start":1784314380049,"end":1784314380052}},"id":"prt_f716cbf0f001H8WYt3j0f8G1yB","sessionID":"ses_08ea082cdffeOdjcwgjfes92M1","messageID":"msg_f716bf9500018pbD4Pohv7CsVy"}}
